Day – 3

#	What is Git/ GitHub / GitLab
1. Git
•	Definition: A distributed version control system created by Linus Torvalds in 2005.
•	Purpose: Tracks changes in source code, allows multiple developers to work together without overwriting each other’s work.
2. GitHub
•	Definition: A cloud-based platform owned by Microsoft that hosts Git repositories.
•	Purpose: Makes collaboration easier by providing a central place to store, share, and review code.
3. GitLab
•	Definition: An open-source DevOps platform that also hosts Git repositories.
•	Purpose: Provides a complete software development lifecycle in one application.

 #Git command                                                                                                                              
o	git add . → Stages all changes in the current directory for commit.
o	git commit -m "message" → Saves staged changes with a descriptive message.
o	git push → Uploads local commits to the remote repository.
o	git pull → Fetches and merges changes from the remote repository into your branch.
o	git branch → Lists, creates, or deletes branches.
o	git fetch → Downloads changes from remote without merging them.
o	git stash → Temporarily saves uncommitted changes for later use.
o	git checkout → Switches branches or restores files.
o	git checkout(branchout) → Switches to the specified branch.

#Python Virtual Environment Commands
•	python -m venv venv → Creates a virtual environment named venv.
•	python -m venv shakthi → Creates a virtual environment named shakthi.
•	shakthi/Scripts/activate → Activates the shakthi virtual environment.
•	deactivate → Exits the current virtual environment.
